::::: {#exr-u2-59}

*Show your working clearly.*

A trapezium has parallel sides of length $4$ cm and $k$ cm, a perpendicular height of $\sqrt{3}$ cm, and an area of $5\sqrt{6}$ cm².

**(a)** Show that $k = 10\sqrt{2}-4$.

::: {.callout-tip collapse="true"}
## 🔍 View Solution

**a)**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{(4+k)\sqrt{3}}{2}=5\sqrt{6} \\ 4+k=10\sqrt{2} \\ k=10\sqrt{2}-4
\end{aligned}
$$

:::


